<TITLE> Shahjahan Siraj, Mollah get bail; Orion boss asked to surrender </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, January 25 (bdnews24.com)The High Court on Sunday granted bail to former BNP minister Shahjahan Siraj in a tax dodging case, and directed Orion Group Chairman Obaidul Karim to surrender within four weeks in four corruption cases, while the Supreme Court granted bail to Awami League lawmaker Habibur Rahman Mollah in an illegal wealth case. A HC bench of justices Mirza Hossain Haider and Borhan Uddin awarded three months' bail to Siraj on a petition filed by the former minister. The court also ordered the National Board of Revenue and Dhaka Special Judge's Court to show cause in four weeks why Siraj's conviction and sentence should not be declared illegal. NBR filed a case against Siraj during emergency alleging that he had evaded tax on money spent for the wedding of his daughter, barrister Sarowat Siraj Shukla. Dhaka Special Judge convicted the fugitive ex-minister on August 29, 2007 and sentenced him to 8 years imprisonment. He surrendered before the HC on Sunday and sought bail. Barrister AHM Shamsuddin Chowdhury Manik moved the petition for Siraj, while Deputy Attorney General Nahid Mahtab opposed it. Mollah too gets bail The Supreme Court granted six months bail to Awami League lawmaker Habibur Rahman Mollah on Sunday in an illegal wealth case. A four-member Appellate Division bench, headed by Chief Justice MM Ruhul Amin, also stayed the proceeding of the case for six months. The court also granted Mollah leave to appeal against the High Court judgment that declared proceedings of the case valid. The Anticorruption Commission filed the case against Mollah with Ramna police station on October 3, 2007 for amassing assets beyond known sources of income. Habibur Rahman Mollah surrendered to the Dhaka Special Judge's Court on November 20, 2007, and was sent to jail. Ajmamul Hossain, QC moved the appeal for Habibur Rahman Mollah on Sunday, while advocate Khurshid Alam Khan opposed it for ACC. Obaidul ordered to surrender The High Court on Sunday directed Orion Group Chairman Obaidul Karim to surrender to the trial court within four weeks in four corruption cases. Barrister AHM Shamsuddin Chowdhury Manik told bdnews24.com that Obaidul Karim appeared before the HC and sought bail in the cases. A HC bench of justices Mir Hasmat Ali and Shamim Hasnain awarded on hearing petitions filed by the fugitive Karim. "The court also ordered the law enforcers not to arrest or harass him before his surrender," said his lawyer Manik who moved the petitions for Karim. Advocate Khan Saifur Rahman opposed t
